                                <foliation>Modern foliation in pencil, 1-23A, 23B-115. <locus from="85" to="115" scheme="folios"/>: older modern foliation, <quote>89-119</quote>, struck out. <secFol>mundum domini qui conditor</secFol>
                                </foliation>
                                <collation>
                                    <formula>1(12, lacks 1 and 12), 2-3(12), 4(16), 5-7(12), 8(8), 9(14), 10(8)</formula>
                                    <p>
                                        <ref target="https://vceditor.library.upenn.edu/project/67c7100f6c70ed00010c26b3/viewOnly">VisColl collation</ref>
                                    </p>
                                    <p>Parchment guards.</p>
                                    <signatures>The manuscript exhibits four types of contemporary quire signatures, one of which is written over the previous type, revealing three separate series of numbering, which indicates that the different codicological units were assembled and rebound already in the middle ages: quire 1 is unmarked; quire 2, is marked with an abbreviated <quote>secundus</quote> inside a square frame in red ink (<locus from="22v" to="22v" scheme="folios"/>), the only signature of this kind. Quire 3 is marked with <quote>tertius</quote> written out (<locus from="33v" to="33v" scheme="folios"/>), and quire 4 with <quote>iiii<hi rend="super">us</hi>
                                        </quote> written on the first folio of the quire (<locus from="34r" to="34r" scheme="folios"/>), possibly in the same hand, and possibly also on its last folio (<locus from="49v" to="49v" scheme="folios"/>). These quires transmit Alain of Lille's <foreign xml:lang="la">Ars praedicatoria</foreign>, and the quire numbers correspond to the current structure. Quires 5-8, which transmit four collections of glosses and excerpts, seem to have once made up a separate unit: the signatures exhibit two layers, of which the first consists of Roman ordinal numerals, <quote>I<hi rend="super">us</hi>
                                        </quote> to <quote>IIII<hi rend="super">us</hi>
                                        </quote>, in red ink (<locus from="61v" to="61v" scheme="folios"/> (partially erased), <locus from="73v" to="73v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="85v" to="85v" scheme="folios"/>, <locus from="93v" to="93v" scheme="folios"/>); for the second layer, a different, contemporary hand has added a <quote>v</quote> in brown ink in front of the previous number (<quote>IIII<hi rend="super">us</hi>
                                        </quote> is simply crossed out and the second hand has added <quote>IX<hi rend="super">us</hi>
                                        </quote> instead). These numbers are, however, ahead by one compared to the current structure. Quire 9, beginning the <foreign xml:lang="la">Liber soliloquiorum</foreign> by Psuedo-Augustine, is simply numbered as <quote>XI<hi rend="super">us</hi>
                                        </quote> in the same hand as the second layer of 5-8 (<locus from="107v" to="107v" scheme="folios"/>). A quire bearing the number X is thus missing, indicating that one full quire has been lost. The texts which remain are, however, complete.</signatures>
                                </collation>
                            </supportDesc>
                        </objectDesc>
                        <additions>
                            <p>
