                    <history>
                        <origin>
                            <p>
                                <origPlace>
                                    <placeName cert="low" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100089">Uppsala</placeName>
                                </origPlace>
                                <origDate notAfter="1400" notBefore="1351">14th century, second half</origDate>. The script used in the first two codicological units, cursiva antiquior, is mainly seen in Austria, Bohemia, Germany and Scandinavia. It does not occur before the second quarter of the 14th century and few examples exist after the beginning of the 15th century (<bibl>
                                    <title type="short" ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/bibl/107413">Derolez (2006)</title>
                                    <citedRange from="134" to="134" unit="page"/>
                                </bibl>). The mix of double- and single-compartment <quote>a</quote> seen in the last part of the manuscript identifies this as a late variant of the script. The colophon on <locus from="49r" to="49r" scheme="folios"/> gives the year <date when="1374"/> for the completion of this section, and <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100536">Brocman</persName>, in a note on <locus from="LCI" to="LCI" scheme="other"/>, dates the manuscript to <date when="1360"/> based on the type of paper. <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100536">Brocman's</persName> identification of the contents of <locus from="50ra" to="67rb" scheme="folios"/> as explanations of difficult words in the <foreign xml:lang="la">Breviarium Upsalense</foreign> would seem to indicate <placeName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/place/100089">Uppsala</placeName> as the origin.</p>
                        </origin>
                        <provenance>
                            <p>Previously no. 195 in the collection of <persName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/person/100536">Nils Reinhold Brocman</persName>, book collector and librarian at the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">Royal Library</orgName> and <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName>. Upon his death in <date when="1770"/>, a large part of his book collection was donated to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName>.</p>
                        </provenance>
                        <acquisition>
                            <p>Transferred to the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100004">National Library</orgName> from the <orgName ref="https://www.manuscripta.se/org/100059">Antiquities Archive</orgName>.</p>
                        </acquisition>
                    </history>
